f liberal internationalism, focusing in particular on three intellectual languages – international law, philosophy and history – through which it was promulgated. Finally, it traces the impact of these ideas across the defining moment of the First World War. The liberal internationalist vision of the late-nineteenth century remained popular well into the twentieth century and forms an important backdrop to the development of the academic study of International Relations in Britain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternationalism. 0aLiberalismxHistoryy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aLiberalismxHistoryy20th centuryzGreat Britain. 4aInternational Relations 2019. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aFirst World War.  aenacting justice.  agenerating order.  ainternational affairs.  ainternational relations.  alate nineteenth century.  aliberal internationalism.  apolitical discourse.  asecuring progress.1 aSylvest, Casper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779350840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793508423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793508/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles